  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="TolE0296">
<l>ñakārai yoṟṟiya toḻiṟpeyar muṉṉa</l>
<l>rallatu kiḷappiṉum vēṟṟumaik kaṇṇum</l>
<l>valleḻut tiyaiyi ṉavveḻuttu mikumē</l>
<l>yukaram varuta lāvayi ṉāṉa</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>After nouns ending in <foreign xml:lang="ta">au</foreign></l>
<l>the appearance of plosives is not forbidden</l>
<l>either in case-relationship or in non-case relationship.</l>
<l>Great scholars opine that it is preferable</l>
<l>to insert <foreign xml:lang="ta">u</foreign> in both cases.<note
              place="foot">i.e., after the two words <foreign xml:lang="ta">kau</foreign> ' seizing ' and <foreign xml:lang="ta">vau</foreign> ' snatching ', one may either double the
          plosive or insert <foreign xml:lang="ta">u,</foreign> but the second alternative is preferable : <foreign xml:lang="ta">kau + kaṭitu &gt; kauvukkaṭitu.</foreign></note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
</text>
